‘I’m not gonna say anything, I just came to drive a truck,’ President Joe Biden joked during his visit to a Mack Trucks plant yesterday where he introduced new rules regarding the U.S. government’s ‘buy American’ policies. Under current regulations, the federal government must use taxpayer dollars to buy products only with at least 55% American-made content. ‘55% is not high enough,’ Biden said during his remarks, saying he is pushing for a 75% requirement by 2029.

node.text:
On July 28, the FDA announced that pharmacists will be able to change out a more expensive name-brand insulin product for a generic, but equally effective substitute called Semglee.⁠
⁠
Semglee's FDA approval is a first for an 'interchangeable' biosimilar for insulin in the U.S. 'This is a momentous day for people who rely daily on insulin for treatment of diabetes, as biosimilar and interchangeable biosimilar products have the potential to greatly reduce health care costs,' said acting FDA Commissioner Dr. Janet Woodcock.⁠
⁠
For the 34M+ people in the U.S. living with diabetes, paying for insulin—an injection that helps the body stabilize blood sugar levels—can be a battle in itself. According to the AP, the cost for a month's supply of a brand-name insulin product like Lantus can cost between $340 and $520. For Semglee, that cost comes down to between $150 and $190 for a month's supply if an individual doesn't have insurance. ⁠
⁠
The development of generic insulin products has often received blowback from brand-name drugmakers. But the growing use of biosimilars across the medical industry from 2020 to 2024 is expected to save patients and health plans alike more than $100 billion, according to the AP.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Walmart recently announced an update to its educational assistance program, saying that both Walmart and Sam's Club will cover the total cost of college tuition and books for any employees who enroll at one of 10 different academic partner institutions. The retail giants employ an estimated 1.5M people who will be eligible to participate in this benefit.⁠
The announcement comes as many giant retail corporations are facing challenges hiring or retaining staffers in a tight labor market. According to data from the Dept of Labor, more than 970,000 retail jobs went unfilled in the month of May. Walmart recently also raised its minimum hourly wages for hundreds of thousands of employees, from $11 to $13, to address its current challenges in the labor market. However, that figure is still $2 less than competitors like Amazon and Target, which both offer a $15 wage.⁠
Colleges & universities participating in the Walmart partnership are: Johnson & Wales Univ., the Univ. of Arizona, the Univ. of Denver, Pathstream, Brandman Univ., Penn Foster, Purdue Univ.
